posts.name: Anonymous
posts.com:
Listened to pic related

Overall impression is that they're a competent stoner/psych/doom band (basically stoner but with some of the poppier Uncle Acid style - I can hear some QOTSA influence too I think) but they're a bit like Acid Mammoth in that they're playing all the right stuff but are kind of boring.

Elements in their favour are that their bass player is quite strong and has an interesting tone during the mini solos in 'All is Fine', though that song in particular runs out of steam half way through. The songs in general could be trimmed a bit imo, I'm not sure why 5-8mins is so normal for this genre - if you want people to groove you need to keep it tight.

'Electric Traveller', one of two singles from the album, starts strong but falls victim to this issue Aawks seem to have where they run out of gas mid-song and the groove grinds to a halt, then chugs along at half the pace for no reason. It does this weird tempo change a few times, kind of like the band had a few different ideas and duct-taped them together rather than making it sound coherent.

'Space City', the other single, is a bit tighter and has an interesting chorus with slightly dissonant vocals, but despite a relatively stable tempo it still sounds a bit disjointed and doesn't really spark much interest.

It's hard to put my finger on why I don't care for it exactly, it just sounds kind of stock and uninspired overall. It's like if I got an AI to generate a stoner/psych sound it would come out with this, in the same way that if I asked it to make generic stoner metal it would produce Acid Mammoth. By the end of the album it's hard to remember any song in particular, it all blends together because the overall sound is pretty uniform despite sections not always fitting together neatly.

It has a lot of the right elements for this type of music but is missing that secret ingredient that gets you hooked on the sound.

I enjoyed King so I thought I'd give Gnome's first album a listen

It's enjoyable, but it's clear they hadn't quite nailed down their formula yet. The vocals in King are sparse but they do add to it a bit, Father of Time is almost all instrumental.

The songs are also far too long. Gnome have a knack for creating fun, groovy riffs, but really the concept only sustains maybe 4 minutes (5 at the outside) of a track, after that it starts to drag. For the second album they seem to have realised this and cut everything down to 3-5mins, with the single Wenceslas at a tight 3:09, which is perfect for that concept

Strangely, I'm not sure if the bass heard on the album is actually a bass. If you watch this video, they used to use two guitars - in the comments they mention they tuned one of the guitars an octave lower and ran it through a bass amp, but switched to an actual bass later on. Very bizarre

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=cuzIBRfzdl4

Overall it's very competent and enjoyable, it's worth a listen for fans of groovier stoner but it didn't quite get me hooked. Father of Time is better than like 80-90% of stoner coming out these days, but their second album was a big improvement.

Suggested tracks: Jebediah Supreme, Rat King

>By going to the record store and saying "hey wheres that record I heard on the radio I'll buy it - oh it sucks".

When you went to the record store, you could hear albums there and get recommendations from the staff and from other people hanging out.

People talked about music, word of mouth was huge, and people socialized so you could hear an album at your friend's house or at a party. Also, musicians toured, with lesser known bands opening shows. And there were music festivals with headliners and up-and-comers.

In the late 60s/early 70s, there was 'free form' radio on FM stations in some cities. This was an anything goes format. Entire albums might get payed so you could hear the whole thing.

Not being able to preview every song an album (as with Spotify) had pluses and minuses. Sure, if you bought a record from an unfamilar artist based on one hit, you could get burned by a lousy album. But it also meant good artists weren't compelled to make every song ear candy. And, it built a suspense and aura of mytique around getting a really good album and dicovering it for yourself at home.

>>114822635
A lot of the stuff you will find is on Youtube. Some good channels to start with are Ambiance, Choonupper, and Mr Fredricks.

Ambiance has a lot of "Intelligent" DnB, known for smooth jazzy sounds and a calmer aesthetic. A lot of his uploads consist of mixes and sets from Good Looking Records, a record label consisting of people who were known for producing a lot of Intelligent DnB.

Choonupper is a really, really old and dead channel. His stuff is a mix, he tends to have newer stuff from the late 90's and early 2000's. Still calm stuff, but a bit different from Ambiance's uploads. A lot more vocalized stuff too.

Mr. Fredricks has a lot of stuff. His uploads of sets and mixes is very similar to Ambiance's, but with a tad more "dark" DnB.
(I am in love with his upload of Blick's "Artemis vs. Shogun" mix.)

There's many more youtube mixes and uploads of sets, but those are the main channels I use for my listening. If you want to get into more dark DnB, Most Metelheadz mixes will cover you there, and if you want techno mixed with DnB, the OST's from the first few wipE′out″ games are packed with great music.

While I have been listening to this genre for about 2 years now, I'm still a noob. Listen to other anons here and find what you like, it's a great genre that has sadly died and has been somewhat lost to time.

>>114825113
>I realized that the Les Paul guitar is the only electric guitar that is made in America. Why is this so?
It has to do with the cost of labour. It's cheaper to manufacture the guitars in countries like Indonesia or China. If you paid to manufacture guitars in America the prices would jump to several thousands of dollars, which is the case with the Les Paul, or any other guitar built by local luthiers. If you wanted the reduce the cost of labour to produce cheaper guitars, you'd have to build factories, which existed in America at a time where the cost of labour wasn't as high as it is now in America.
And it doesn't mean the cheaper cost of labour and lower cost of living in Indonesia or China, for example, are bad. Indonesian or Chinese guitars are of excellent quality, their only defects are because they're built in factories where perfectionism isn't possible. Hand-built guitars will obviously be of better quality (although it's not always the case).
I've seen a video of a guy who ordered a custom Jackson from an American workshop for almost 4000$ and he filmed all the QC issues that came with it: dings and scratches on the body, fucked up inlays, sharp fret ends, etc. So American guitars aren't necessarily better. My 300$ Chinese Jackson is fucking perfect.
So unless you buy a Chinese noname off eBay, you'll probably get a very nice guitar. The Indonesian or Chinese workers aren't exploited either, selling a 500$ guitar is the same for them as an American selling a 1200$ guitar.

OP, there is no quick scheme or life hack to apply when it comes to enjoying free jazz. The music theory route is unironically a meme, since part of the point of free jazz was to do away with as much theory as possible. This is why any moron on here who says you need to be a theorycel to get free form music is a fucking pretentious pseud with a shallow understanding of basic jazz history. Just look into Ornette Coleman's ideas on why he made free jazz to see what I'm talking about.
I think the first free jazz I ever heard was Coltrane's Meditations. I was already a huge fan of earlier work like My Favorite Things and A Love Supreme, but that album just filtered me hard. I was a retarded teenager back then, so because I didn't understand the album then, I coped with the usual buzzwords and talking points that pseuds still over rely on to this day. "Pretentious wankery, people only pretend to like it to seem smart", etc.
But fast-forward a couple of years and I start to understand free jazz. Mainly because of Pharoah Sanders who makes far more accessible and melodic kinds of free form music (it's not a coincidence that my favorite part of Ascension is his solo), but that then allowed me to work my way up to the more chaotic shit done by Trane.
There's really no insight or tip that's going to help you magically appreciate it. You just have to go back to it and see if you can decipher what's going on in an intuitive sense, not a theoretical one. It's like learning a new language - it will always come off as gibberish to you, but once you soak it in over time, things start revealing themselves to you. There's no other way to do it. Just come back to this music every now and then when you're in the mood. Maybe it will click for you, maybe it won't.
And don't fall for the "2deep4u" meme. Like I already said, free jazz isn't about the intellect. If you think it is, you're already setting yourself up for failure.

>>114820499
I don't think it's necessarily a board culture thing, if anything it's a shift in music, internet and attention economies. back then 4chan could exist in a more vastly dispersed internet, alongside a wide array of miscellaneous niche websites. Information was difficult to agregate so in many ways this place became an unofficial hub that was convenient to anonymously exist in. what became novel on this board could thus carry more weight and influence the general internet consesnus. nowadays, anonimity is no longer the norm, music discovery is easier than ever, and information/internet traffic is more centralized than ever. whatever reach we had, is no longer possible. if anything we're lucky that we're not as slow as other blue boards. there's still novelty to this place but we're well past a heyday that will likely never come back
